## Todo File Management Rules (.context/todos/[{task_name}].md)

### CRITICAL: Task Preservation Policy
- **NEVER DELETE OR REMOVE COMPLETED TASKS** - Tasks are permanent project history
- **ONLY UPDATE CHECKBOXES** - Change `[ ]` to `[x]` when tasks are completed
- **PRESERVE ALL TASK DESCRIPTIONS** - Maintain exact wording and details of completed tasks
- **MAINTAIN TASK HIERARCHY** - Keep sub-tasks and nested items intact when parent tasks complete

### Todo File Structure Requirements
Each todo file MUST follow this exact format:

# [Category] Todo List

## Description
Detailed description of this todo category's purpose, including:
- ALWAYS USE CHECKBOXES for all actionable items
- What types of tasks belong here
- How tasks should be tracked
- When and how to update this file
- How this category relates to the project
- Any specific guidelines or requirements
- Any relevant context about the status of the tasks implementation
- No pseudo code or implementations. Only detailed steps on how to achieve such things.
- **CRITICAL: Mark items complete with checkbox when completed. NEVER REMOVE COMPLETED TASKS.**
- **CRITICAL: Update this todo regularly as tasks and subtasks are completed to insure the projects current state is accurately reflected in this file.**

### Task Status Management
- **Active Tasks**: `[ ]` - Currently being worked on or ready to start
- **Completed Tasks**: `[x]` - Finished tasks that MUST remain in the file permanently
- **Blocked Tasks**: `[?]` - Tasks waiting on dependencies or decisions
- **Deferred Tasks**: `[-]` - Tasks postponed but not abandoned

### Memory Section Guidelines
- ALWAYS maintain the Memory section in each todo file
- UPDATE the Memory section when:
  - Making significant implementation decisions
  - Overcoming technical challenges
  - Discovering future considerations
  - Gaining new technical insights
  - Adding or modifying dependencies
- ENSURE the Memory section:
  - Provides clear context for future development
  - Documents rationale behind decisions
  - Tracks evolution of implementation
  - Records lessons learned
  - Notes potential improvements
- USE the Memory section to:
  - Aid in knowledge transfer
  - Support maintenance decisions
  - Guide future enhancements
  - Prevent repeated mistakes
  - Maintain implementation context

### Todo File Organization Structure
Organize tasks by logical phases and hierarchical breakdown, not by completion status:

## Phase 1: [Phase Name]
- [ ] Major task or milestone
  - [ ] Subtask 1
  - [ ] Subtask 2
    - [ ] Sub-subtask if needed
  - [x] Completed subtask
- [x] Completed major task
  - [x] All subtasks also marked complete
  - [x] With completion dates

## Phase 2: [Next Phase Name]
- [ ] Next major milestone
  - [ ] Associated subtasks
- [ ] Additional tasks for this phase

## Phase N: [Future Phase]
- [ ] Future milestones
- [ ] Long-term objectives

## Memory
- Key decisions made during implementation
- Technical challenges overcome
- Future considerations discovered
- Dependencies and architectural choices

### Project Management Integration
- If the user references any .context/todos/*.md ALWAYS consider them before making changes
- AUTOMATICALLY update relevant todo files in .context/todos/ when:
  - Tasks are completed or change status (update checkbox only)
  - New tasks are identified (add to appropriate section)
  - Implementation status changes (move between sections if needed)
  - Technical debt is discovered (add to appropriate section)
- MAINTAIN separate todo files for different task categories:
  - .context/todos/feature-name.md - Feature-specific tasks
  - .context/todos/technical-debt.md - Technical debt and refactoring
  - .context/todos/bugs.md - Bug tracking and fixes
  - .context/todos/documentation.md - Documentation tasks

### Todo Update Workflow
1. **When completing a task**:
   - Change `[ ]` to `[x]`
   - Keep task in its original phase/location
   - Update Memory section with any relevant insights

2. **When adding new tasks**:
   - Add to appropriate phase section
   - Use hierarchical structure (tasks → subtasks → sub-subtasks)
   - Use clear, actionable descriptions
   - Include context and acceptance criteria

3. **When tasks become blocked**:
   - Change to `[?]` status
   - Document blocking issue in task description
   - Keep task in its original phase location

4. **When tasks are deferred**:
   - Change to `[-]` status
   - Document reason for deferral
   - Keep task in its original phase location

5. **When organizing tasks**:
   - Group related tasks under logical phases
   - Use indentation to show task hierarchy
   - Break down complex tasks into manageable subtasks
   - Maintain chronological or logical phase ordering
